To generate a table of contents automatically in a LaTeX document, you need to use the `\tableofcontents` command. Here's an example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

% Package for better TOC appearance (optional)
\usepackage{tocloft}

% Customize TOC (optional)
\renewcommand{\cftsecfont}{\normalfont\bfseries}
\renewcommand{\cftsecpagefont}{\normalfont}

\begin{document}

% Generates the table of contents
\tableofcontents

% Add sections and subsections for the TOC to reference
\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction.

\subsection{Background}
This is the background.

\section{Main Body}
This is the main body.

\subsection{First Topic}
This is the first topic.

\subsection{Second Topic}
This is the second topic.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion.

\end{document}
```

In this example, we first include the `tocloft` package (optional) to customize the appearance of the table of contents. Then, we use `\renewcommand` to change the font style for section and page numbers in the TOC.

The `\tableofcontents` command is placed where you want the table of contents to appear in the document.

Sections and subsections are added using `\section` and `\subsection` commands. As you add these, LaTeX will automatically update the table of contents with the appropriate entries and page numbers.

To draw a chessboard in LaTeX using FEN notation, we can use the `chessboard` package. Here's an example code:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\newcommand{\chessboardFEN}{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

\begin{center}
\chessboard[setfen=\chessboardFEN]
\end{center}

\end{document}
```

In this code, we first import the `chessboard` package. Then, we define a new command `\chessboardFEN` that contains the FEN notation of the chessboard state we want to display. In this example, the FEN notation represents the starting position of a chess game.

Finally, we use the `\chessboard` command to display the board, passing the `setfen` option with the value of `\chessboardFEN`. The resulting chessboard will be centered using the `center` environment.

You can replace the `\chessboardFEN` command with any FEN notation you need to display a different chessboard state.

